{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775856962091,"sessionID":"ses_286ad6f16ffesjUNLGKzJUQsJL","part":{"id":"prt_d7952bff6001sz53ZNDzA9OfmQ","messageID":"msg_d7952b34c001C2pEwi6OU2p2eT","sessionID":"ses_286ad6f16ffesjUNLGKzJUQsJL","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_5103d30e51c0437eb3c74218","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-013/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-013/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: Redis Storage Implementation (AR-013)\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement the Redis backend for the session storage interface in `pkg/store`, providing persistent sandbox metadata storage with indexed queries for garbage collection based on expiry and last-activity timestamps.\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Purpose\n10: \n11: The Redis storage implementation provides the primary backend for session persistence in the agentcube project. It enables:\n12: \n13: 1. **Session persistence**: Store and retrieve sandbox information using Redis key-value storage\n14: 2. **Garbage collection support**: Maintain sorted set indices for expiry and last-activity based cleanup\n15: 3. **Production-ready storage**: Redis is the default and recommended backend for production deployments\n16: 4. **Atomic operations**: Use Redis pipelines to ensure consistent index updates\n17: \n18: This implementation is the focus of AR-013 and builds upon the interface defined in AR-012.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Scope\n23: \n24: ### In Scope\n25: \n26: - `pkg/store/store_redis.go` - Redis implementation using `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9`\n27: - `sessionKey()` helper function for consistent key construction\n28: - `makeRedisOptions()` for environment variable parsing and client configuration\n29: - All `Store` interface methods implemented with Redis commands\n30: - Pipeline operations for atomic multi-command operations\n31: - Unit tests with mocked Redis client\n32: - Integration tests with real Redis instance (Docker-based)\n33: \n34: ### Out of Scope\n35: \n36: - Valkey implementation (separate AR or combined with AR-012)\n37: - Alternative storage backends (etcd, Consul, etc.)\n38: - Redis cluster configuration and sharding strategies\n39: - Connection pooling tuning beyond default settings\n40: \n41: ---\n42: \n43: ## Impact Analysis\n44: \n45: ### Dependencies\n46: \n47: | Package | Purpose |\n48: |---------|---------|\n49: | `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` | Redis client library |\n50: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging (if needed for error reporting) |\n51: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | `SandboxInfo` type definitions |\n52: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/store` | Store interface (from AR-012) |\n53: \n54: ### Affected Components\n55: \n56: 1. **Sandbox Orchestrator**: Will use `Storage()` to persist sandbox metadata\n57: 2. **Garbage Collector**: Will use `ListExpiredSandboxes` and `ListInactiveSandboxes` for cleanup operations\n58: 3. **Session Manager**: Will use `UpdateSessionLastActivity` for activity tracking\n59: 4. **Configuration System**: Must provide `REDIS_ADDR` and `REDIS_PASSWORD` environment variables\n60: \n61: ### Backward Compatibility\n62: \n63: - This is a new implementation of an existing interface\n64: - No breaking changes to the `Store` interface\n65: - Configuration via environment variables (no config file changes)\n66: \n67: ### Risk Assessment\n68: \n69: | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n70: |------|------------|--------|------------|\n71: | Redis connection failures | Medium | High | `Ping()` method for health checks; connection retry in client library |\n72: | ZSET index inconsistency | Low | High | Atomic pipeline operations ensure all-or-nothing updates |\n73: | Password misconfiguration | Medium | High | Clear error messages; `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false` escape hatch |\n74: | Memory bloat from orphaned ZSET members | Low | Medium | List methods tolerate missing keys; periodic cleanup recommended |\n75: | Pipeline command failures | Low | Medium | Check all pipeline results; return descriptive errors |\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: ## Alternatives Considered\n80: \n81: ### Alternative 1: Hash-Based Storage\n82: \n83: **Approach**: Store session data as Redis Hash instead of JSON string\n84: \n85: **Pros**:\n86: - Partial field updates without full serialization\n87: - More efficient for small field changes\n88: - Native Redis type\n89: \n90: **Cons**:\n91: - Complex nested structures (`EntryPoints` array) awkward in hashes\n92: - JSON marshaling already required for `SandboxInfo` type\n93: - Less portable if switching to other backends\n94: \n95: **Decision**: Use JSON string storage for simplicity and consistency.\n96: \n97: ### Alternative 2: TTL-Only Expiration\n98: \n99: **Approach**: Rely solely on Redis native TTL instead of maintaining `session:expiry` ZSET\n100: \n101: **Pros**:\n102: - Simpler implementation\n103: - Automatic expiration handled by Redis\n104: - Reduced memory footprint\n105: \n106: **Cons**:\n107: - Cannot efficiently query \"sessions expiring before time X\"\n108: - Last-activity tracking still requires ZSET\n109: - Inconsistent semantics between expiry and activity indices\n110: \n111: **Decision**: Maintain explicit ZSET indices for efficient range queries required by garbage collection.\n112: \n113: ### Alternative 3: Lua Script for Atomicity\n114: \n115: **Approach**: Use Lua scripts for `StoreSandbox` and `DeleteSandboxBySessionID` instead of pipelines\n116: \n117: **Pros**:\n118: - True atomic execution on Redis server\n119: - Reduced network round trips\n120: - More \"Redis-native\" approach\n121: \n122: **Cons**:\n123: - More complex code and debugging\n124: - Harder to test and maintain\n125: - Pipelines provide sufficient atomicity for this use case\n126: \n127: **Decision**: Use Redis pipelines for better code clarity and easier testing.\n128: \n129: ---\n130: \n131: ## Implementation Details\n132: \n133: ### Redis Store Structure\n134: \n135: ```go\n136: type redisStore struct {\n137:     cli                  *redisv9.Client\n138:     sessionPrefix        string\n139:     expiryIndexKey       string\n140:     lastActivityIndexKey string\n141: }\n142: ```\n143: \n144: ### Key Patterns\n145: \n146: | Purpose | Key Pattern |\n147: |---------|-------------|\n148: | Session data | `session:{sessionId}` |\n149: | Expiry index | `session:expiry` |\n150: | Last activity index | `session:last_activity` |\n151: \n152: ### Connection Configuration\n153: \n154: ```go\n155: func makeRedisOptions() (*redisv9.Options, error) {\n156:     redisAddr := os.Getenv(\"REDIS_ADDR\")\n157:     if redisAddr == \"\" {\n158:         return nil, errors.New(\"REDIS_ADDR is required\")\n159:     }\n160:     \n161:     redisPassword := os.Getenv(\"REDIS_PASSWORD\")\n162:     passwordRequired := true\n163:     if v := os.Getenv(\"REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED\"); strings.EqualFold(v, \"false\") {\n164:         passwordRequired = false\n165:     }\n166:     \n167:     if passwordRequired && redisPassword == \"\" {\n168:         return nil, errors.New(\"REDIS_PASSWORD is required (set REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false to disable)\")\n169:     }\n170:     \n171:     return &redisv9.Options{\n172:         Addr:     redisAddr,\n173:         Password: redisPassword,\n174:     }, nil\n175: }\n176: ```\n177: \n178: ### Method Implementation Summary\n179: \n180: | Method | Redis Commands | Notes |\n181: |--------|----------------|-------|\n182: | `Ping` | `PING` | Expect `PONG` response |\n183: | `GetSandboxBySessionID` | `GET session:{id}` | Return `ErrNotFound` on nil |\n184: | `StoreSandbox` | Pipeline: `SETNX`, `ZADD expiry`, `ZADD last_activity` | Validate non-nil and non-zero ExpiresAt |\n185: | `UpdateSandbox` | `SET key value XX` | Return error if key doesn't exist |\n186: | `DeleteSandboxBySessionID` | Pipeline: `DEL`, `ZREM expiry`, `ZREM last_activity` | Clean up all references |\n187: | `ListExpiredSandboxes` | `ZRANGEBYSCORE session:expiry -inf {before.Unix} LIMIT 0 limit` + pipeline GETs | Skip missing keys |\n188: | `ListInactiveSandboxes` | `ZRANGEBYSCORE session:last_activity -inf {before.Unix} LIMIT 0 limit` + pipeline GETs | Skip missing keys |\n189: | `UpdateSessionLastActivity` | `GET` (check exists), then `ZADD session:last_activity` | Return `ErrNotFound` if missing |\n190: | `Close` | `cli.Close()` | Close Redis connection |\n191: \n192: ### Atomicity Guarantees\n193: \n194: - `StoreSandbox`: Pipeline ensures all-or-nothing for SETNX + ZADD + ZADD\n195: - `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`: Pipeline ensures all-or-nothing for DEL + ZREM + ZREM\n196: - `UpdateSandbox`: Single `SET XX` command is atomic\n197: \n198: ### Error Handling\n199: \n200: - `redis.Nil` → `store.ErrNotFound`\n201: - Connection errors → wrapped with context\n202: - Pipeline errors → fail fast with descriptive message\n203: \n204: ---\n205: \n206: ## Configuration Reference\n207: \n208: ### Environment Variables\n209: \n210: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n211: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n212: | `REDIS_ADDR` | Yes | - | Host:port format (e.g., `localhost:6379`) |\n213: | `REDIS_PASSWORD` | Conditional | - | Required unless `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false` |\n214: | `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | No | `true` | Case-insensitive boolean |\n215: | `STORE_TYPE` | No | `redis` | Must be `redis` or empty for this implementation |\n216: \n217: ---\n218: \n219: ## Testing Strategy\n220: \n221: ### Unit Tests\n222: \n223: 1. **TestRedisStore_Ping_Success**: Mock `PING` returns `PONG`\n224: 2. **TestRedisStore_GetSandboxBySessionID_NotFound**: Mock `GET` returns `nil`\n225: 3. **TestRedisStore_StoreSandbox_NilRejected**: Validate input validation\n226: 4. **TestRedisStore_StoreSandbox_Success**: Verify pipeline commands\n227: 5. **TestRedisStore_UpdateSandbox_MissingKey**: Verify `SET XX` behavior\n228: 6. **TestRedisStore_DeleteSandboxBySessionID_Success**: Verify cleanup\n229: 7. **TestRedisStore_ListExpiredSandboxes_Empty**: Limit <= 0 returns nil\n230: 8. **TestRedisStore_UpdateSessionLastActivity_NotFound**: Missing session\n231: \n232: ### Integration Tests\n233: \n234: 1. **TestRedisStore_Integration_FullLifecycle**: Full CRUD operations with real Redis\n235: 2. **TestRedisStore_Integration_ConcurrentAccess**: Concurrent store/update/delete\n236: 3. **TestRedisStore_Integration_IndexConsistency**: Verify ZSET consistency after operations\n237: 4. **TestRedisStore_Integration_PasswordAuth**: Test with password authentication\n238: \n239: ### Test Fixtures\n240: \n241: ```go\n242: func newTestRedisStore() (*redisStore, func()) {\n243:     // Use testcontainers-go or dockertest for Redis container\n244:     // Return cleanup function\n245: }\n246: ```\n247: \n248: ---\n249: \n250: ## Acceptance Criteria\n251: \n252: - [ ] `redisStore` struct implements all `Store` interface methods\n253: - [ ] Key patterns match spec: `session:`, `session:expiry`, `session:last_activity`\n254: - [ ] Pipeline operations used for `StoreSandbox` and `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`\n255: - [ ] `ErrNotFound` returned consistently for missing sessions\n256: - [ ] Environment variable parsing matches spec table\n257: - [ ] `makeRedisOptions()` validates required fields\n258: - [ ] All unit tests pass with mocked client\n259: - [ ] Integration tests pass with real Redis instance\n260: - [ ] Code coverage >= 80% for `store_redis.go`\n261: - [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n262: \n263: ---\n264: \n265: ## References\n266: \n267: - Interface Definition: `session-store/design.md`\n268: - Specification: `session-store/spec.md`\n269: - AR-012 Proposal: `changes/AR-012/proposal.md` (base interface work)\n270: - Redis Client Docs: https://github.com/redis/go-redis\n\n(End of file - total 270 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: Redis Storage Implementation (AR-013)\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement the Redis backend for the session storage interface in `pkg/store`, providing persistent sandbox metadata storage with indexed queries for garbage collection based on expiry and last-activity timestamps.\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe Redis storage implementation provides the primary backend for session persistence in the agentcube project. It enables:\n\n1. **Session persistence**: Store and retrieve sandbox information using Redis key-value storage\n2. **Garbage collection support**: Maintain sorted set indices for expiry and last-activity based cleanup\n3. **Production-ready storage**: Redis is the default and recommended backend for production deployments\n4. **Atomic operations**: Use Redis pipelines to ensure consistent index updates\n\nThis implementation is the focus of AR-013 and builds upon the interface defined in AR-012.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-013/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775856962076,"end":1775856962089}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775856962094,"sessionID":"ses_286ad6f16ffesjUNLGKzJUQsJL","part":{"id":"prt_d7952c504001173Jz8AO5ezD3C","messageID":"msg_d7952b34c001C2pEwi6OU2p2eT","sessionID":"ses_286ad6f16ffesjUNLGKzJUQsJL","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_5d99a4372d5340269cfc7f5a","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-012/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-012/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: Session Storage Interface Implementation (AR-012)\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement a session storage interface in `pkg/store` that provides Redis and Valkey backends for persisting sandbox metadata, with indexed queries for garbage collection based on expiry and last-activity timestamps.\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Purpose\n10: \n11: The session storage system provides persistent storage for sandbox session metadata in the agentcube project. It enables:\n12: \n13: 1. **Session persistence**: Store and retrieve sandbox information keyed by session ID\n14: 2. **Garbage collection support**: Index sessions by expiry time and last activity for cleanup operations\n15: 3. **Backend flexibility**: Support both Redis and Valkey storage providers via configuration-based selection\n16: 4. **Singleton access**: Thread-safe initialization and global access pattern\n17: \n18: This implementation is required for AR-012 and supports the broader sandbox orchestration system documented in `sandbox-orchestration/design.md`.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Scope\n23: \n24: ### In Scope\n25: \n26: - `pkg/store/store.go` - Core `Store` interface definition and `ErrNotFound` error\n27: - `pkg/store/singleton.go` - Singleton pattern with `Storage()` and `initStore()` functions\n28: - `pkg/store/store_redis.go` - Redis implementation using `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9`\n29: - `pkg/store/store_valkey.go` - Valkey implementation using `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go`\n30: - Environment variable configuration for both backends\n31: - Index maintenance for expiry and last-activity sorted sets\n32: \n33: ### Out of Scope\n34: \n35: - Database migration logic (stateless key-value store)\n36: - Horizontal scaling considerations for cluster deployments (noted in Valkey MGET slot comment)\n37: - Custom expiration hooks beyond index queries\n38: - Alternative storage backends (e.g., etcd, Consul)\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## Impact Analysis\n43: \n44: ### Dependencies\n45: \n46: | Package | Purpose |\n47: |---------|---------|\n48: | `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` | Redis client library |\n49: | `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` | Valkey client library |\n50: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n51: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | `SandboxInfo` type definitions |\n52: \n53: ### Affected Components\n54: \n55: 1. **Sandbox Orchestrator**: Will use `Storage()` to persist sandbox creation/update/delete operations\n56: 2. **Garbage Collector**: Will use `ListExpiredSandboxes` and `ListInactiveSandboxes` for cleanup\n57: 3. **Session Manager**: Will use `UpdateSessionLastActivity` for activity tracking\n58: \n59: ### Backward Compatibility\n60: \n61: - This is a new module with no existing API contracts\n62: - No migration required (stateless store initialization)\n63: \n64: ### Risk Assessment\n65: \n66: | Risk | Likelihood | Mitigation |\n67: |------|------------|------------|\n68: | Redis/Valkey connection failures | Medium | `Ping()` method for health checks; connection retry logic in client libraries |\n69: | ZSET index inconsistency | Low | Atomic pipeline operations in `StoreSandbox` and `DeleteSandboxBySessionID` |\n70: | Password misconfiguration | Medium | Clear error messages on initialization failure; `*_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` escape hatch |\n71: | Valkey cluster slot conflicts | Low | Document in `loadSandboxesBySessionIDs` that keys must be in same slot |\n72: \n73: ---\n74: \n75: ## Alternatives Considered\n76: \n77: ### Alternative 1: Single Backend (Redis Only)\n78: \n79: **Approach**: Implement only Redis support initially\n80: \n81: **Pros**:\n82: - Simpler codebase\n83: - Faster initial implementation\n84: - Reduced testing surface\n85: \n86: **Cons**:\n87: - Limits deployment flexibility\n88: - Valkey provides better performance characteristics for some workloads\n89: - May require refactor later if Valkey support becomes critical\n90: \n91: **Decision**: Implement both backends in parallel to avoid future refactoring and support diverse deployment scenarios.\n92: \n93: ### Alternative 2: Interface-per-Backend Pattern\n94: \n95: **Approach**: Define separate interfaces for Redis and Valkey instead of a common `Store` interface\n96: \n97: **Pros**:\n98: - Backend-specific optimizations easier to implement\n99: - No abstraction leakage\n100: \n101: **Cons**:\n102: - Caller code must branch on backend type\n103: - Violates dependency inversion principle\n104: - Makes testing harder\n105: \n106: **Decision**: Use a common `Store` interface to enable transparent backend swapping and simplify caller code.\n107: \n108: ### Alternative 3: TTL-Based Expiration Only\n109: \n110: **Approach**: Rely solely on Redis/Valkey native TTL instead of maintaining `session:expiry` ZSET\n111: \n112: **Pros**:\n113: - Simpler implementation\n114: - Leverages built-in expiration\n115: \n116: **Cons**:\n117: - Cannot query \"sessions expiring before time X\" efficiently\n118: - Last-activity tracking still requires ZSET\n119: - Inconsistent semantics between expiry and activity\n120: \n121: **Decision**: Maintain explicit ZSET indices for both expiry and last-activity to support efficient range queries required by garbage collection.\n122: \n123: ### Alternative 4: Hash vs. JSON String Storage\n124: \n125: **Approach**: Store session data as Redis Hash instead of JSON string\n126: \n127: **Pros**:\n128: - Partial field updates possible\n129: - More \"Redis-native\"\n130: \n131: **Cons**:\n132: - Complex nested structures (e.g., `EntryPoints` array) awkward in hashes\n133: - JSON marshaling already required for `SandboxInfo` type\n134: - Less portable across Redis/Valkey client libraries\n135: \n136: **Decision**: Use JSON string storage for simplicity and consistency with `SandboxInfo` type serialization.\n137: \n138: ---\n139: \n140: ## Implementation Plan\n141: \n142: ### Phase 1: Core Interface and Types\n143: \n144: 1. Define `Store` interface with exact method signatures\n145: 2. Define `ErrNotFound` sentinel error\n146: 3. Implement `SandboxInfo` and `SandboxEntryPoint` types in `pkg/common/types` (if not already present)\n147: \n148: ### Phase 2: Singleton Pattern\n149: \n150: 1. Implement `singleton.go` with `sync.Once` initialization\n151: 2. Implement provider selection logic based on `STORE_TYPE`\n152: 3. Add fatal logging on initialization failure\n153: \n154: ### Phase 3: Redis Implementation\n155: \n156: 1. Implement `redisStore` struct with key pattern constants\n157: 2. Implement `makeRedisOptions` for environment variable parsing\n158: 3. Implement all interface methods using Redis commands per spec\n159: 4. Add pipeline/atomic operations for `StoreSandbox` and `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`\n160: \n161: ### Phase 4: Valkey Implementation\n162: \n163: 1. Implement `valkeyStore` struct mirroring Redis structure\n164: 2. Implement `makeValkeyOptions` with cluster-aware options\n165: 3. Implement all interface methods using Valkey fluent API\n166: 4. Add MGET optimization in `loadSandboxesBySessionIDs`\n167: \n168: ### Phase 5: Testing\n169: \n170: 1. Unit tests for each backend with mocked clients\n171: 2. Integration tests with real Redis and Valkey instances (Docker-based)\n172: 3. Test password-required vs. password-optional scenarios\n173: 4. Test ZSET index consistency under concurrent operations\n174: \n175: ---\n176: \n177: ## Configuration Reference\n178: \n179: ### Environment Variables\n180: \n181: | Variable | Backend | Required | Default | Notes |\n182: |----------|---------|----------|---------|-------|\n183: | `STORE_TYPE` | Both | No | `redis` | Case-insensitive: `redis` or `valkey` |\n184: | `REDIS_ADDR` | Redis | Yes | - | Host:port format |\n185: | `REDIS_PASSWORD` | Redis | Conditional | - | Required unless `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false` |\n186: | `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | Redis | No | `true` | Case-insensitive boolean |\n187: | `VALKEY_ADDR` | Valkey | Yes | - | Comma-separated cluster addresses |\n188: | `VALKEY_PASSWORD` | Valkey | Conditional | - | Required unless `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false` |\n189: | `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | Valkey | No | `true` | Case-insensitive boolean |\n190: | `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE` | Valkey | No | `false` | Enable to set `DisableCache=true` |\n191: | `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE` | Valkey | No | `false` | Enable to set `ForceSingleClient=true` |\n192: \n193: ---\n194: \n195: ## Key Design Decisions\n196: \n197: 1. **Pipeline Atomicity**: `StoreSandbox` and `DeleteSandboxBySessionID` use Redis pipelines / Valkey `DoMulti` to ensure atomic index updates\n198: \n199: 2. **NotFound Semantics**: Both backends normalize their native \"nil\" responses to `ErrNotFound` for consistent caller handling\n200: \n201: 3. **UpdateSandbox Validation**: Uses `SET XX` to enforce \"key must exist\" semantics, preventing accidental creation\n202: \n203: 4. **List Tolerance**: `ListExpiredSandboxes` and `ListInactiveSandboxes` skip orphaned ZSET members rather than failing the entire batch\n204: \n205: 5. **Last-Activity Precondition**: `UpdateSessionLastActivity` requires the session key to exist, returning `ErrNotFound` if absent\n206: \n207: ---\n208: \n209: ## Acceptance Criteria\n210: \n211: - [ ] `Store` interface matches exact signatures from spec\n212: - [ ] Redis implementation passes all command patterns from spec table\n213: - [ ] Valkey implementation passes all API patterns from spec table\n214: - [ ] `Storage()` singleton initializes exactly once under concurrent access\n215: - [ ] Provider selection respects `STORE_TYPE` case-insensitivity\n216: - [ ] Password-optional mode works for both backends\n217: - [ ] ZSET indices remain consistent after store/update/delete operations\n218: - [ ] `ErrNotFound` returned consistently for missing sessions\n219: - [ ] All environment variables documented and tested\n220: \n221: ---\n222: \n223: ## References\n224: \n225: - Design: `session-store/design.md`\n226: - Specification: `session-store/spec.md`\n227: - Client-Go: `deployment/client-go.md`\n228: - Sandbox Orchestration: `sandbox-orchestration/design.md`\n\n(End of file - total 228 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: Session Storage Interface Implementation (AR-012)\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement a session storage interface in `pkg/store` that provides Redis and Valkey backends for persisting sandbox metadata, with indexed queries for garbage collection based on expiry and last-activity timestamps.\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe session storage system provides persistent storage for sandbox session metadata in the agentcube project. It enables:\n\n1. **Session persistence**: Store and retrieve sandbox information keyed by session ID\n2. **Garbage collection support**: Index sessions by expiry time and last activity for cleanup operations\n3. **Backend flexibility**: Support both Redis and Valkey storage providers via configuration-based selection\n4. **Singleton access**: Thread-safe initialization and global access pattern\n\nThis implementation is required for AR-012 and supports the broader sandbox orchestration system documented in `sandbox-orchestration/design.md`.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-012/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775856962079,"end":1775856962091}}}}
